## Conversation
User asked to review the ts-v2 decouple stack for correctness, specifically whether too much got promoted into weave/shared. Analysis (grimp importer-bucket sweep, .context/analyze_shared.py) found the shared wire contract was fusing three audiences. User then directed: create a top-level weave/server_worker_shared/ dir with a documented __init__ (their exact words: "put the server_worker_shared dir at the top level with a comment in the init about this decision"), in-repo only (NO core moves yet), and make each move its own PR on the gt stack. This is PR6, stacked on andrew/ts-v2-eval-worker (the prior tip).

## What & why
EvaluateModelArgs / RescoringArgs / EvalWorkerJob / EvaluateModelDispatcher are shared between the trace server (dispatch side) and the eval worker (consume side), NOT between the client SDK and the server. grimp confirmed: their only importers are weave.trace_server.{sqlite,clickhouse}_trace_server* (dispatch) and weave.eval_worker (consume); ZERO client importers. They were living in weave/shared/trace_server_interface.py (the client<->server contract), so the client SDK transitively carried a job contract it never uses. Moved them to a new leaf package weave/server_worker_shared/. EvaluateModelReq/EvaluateModelRes stay in shared -- those ARE client-facing (TraceServerInterface.evaluate_model method, implemented by the client bindings). EvalWorkerJob is unused in-repo (core consumes it) but moved with its union members.

